items.synopsis: Days after being threatened by multiple, large bushfires, communities in the state's east are bracing for flooding as heavy rainfall continues feeding into river systems. Follow live.

title.children: Floodwaters inundate homes in Victoria's east after heavy rain swells major rivers

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Ahead of the flooding, residents in areas such as Tinamba undertook sandbagging in an attempt to stave off the effects of inundation. Locals have already begun to question why it took the region's water authority, Southern Rural Water, so long to begin draining Lake Glenmaggie, which has contributed to the flooding along the Macalister River. Newry dairy farmer Tim Dwyer told the ABC given the weather forecast, the lake should have been drained earlier. "When there was a major flood warning at Licola they only had 4,500 megalitres being released," Mr Dwyer said. "That's not acceptable. "We've had a forecast for this rain for about a week now." But Southern Rural Water's managing director Cameron Fitzgerald has defended the organisation's actions, saying the weather conditions affecting the region exceeded expectations. "Two days ago we had bushfires, we are in an El Nino event and we do need water for people later in the season to be able to continue to grow their produces, fruit and vegetables and create milk," Mr Fitzgerald said. "So we are always thinking about the full balance of how we manage this storage. "Obviously this event was a bit bigger than the event we had planned for," he said.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The three towns under immediate flooding threat are Newry, Tinamba and Tinamba West. Newry is is about 215 kilometres east of Melbourne, and 30 kilometres north-west of Sale. According to the latest census, the town had a population of 451 people. Meanwhile Tinamba and Tinamba West had recorded populations of 358 and 63 respectively.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The State Emergency Service (SES) has told the ABC that up to 130 homes may flood at Newry, Tinamba and Tinamba West. A number of homes have already flooded at Newry. SES Deputy Chief Officer David Baker told ABC News Breakfast floodwaters downstream of Lake Glenmaggie on the Macalister River were already impacting Newry, and within the hour they would hit Tinamba and Tinamba West. "We estimate up to around 130 properties may be impacted by this event, hence why we issued an emergency warning late yesterday afternoon which was renewed again during the early hours of the morning," he said. "Our crews, police and CFA, have spent the afternoon and overnight making sure that people are warned to move to higher ground." The deputy chief said he believed people had largely heeded those warnings.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Federal Labor senator for Victoria Jana Stewart says she's confident people will get behind the proposed Voice to Parliament, as the last leg of campaigning gets underway. There is just over a week until the referendum on October 14, but AEC data shows more than 900,000 Australians have already voted. Senator Stewart says polls that have the No campaign leading don't reflect what people tell her on the ground. "Lots of people as they are going past, they are saying to me 'I am already saying yes'. "There are people who are saying to me as they are walking in it's really simple and they'll say I'm voting yes but I'm not telling my friends because it has been really horrible."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: As you may have heard, a referendum needs a double majority to pass. This is one of its key differences from a federal election. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: In a bid to counter the spreading of disinformation about the referendum, the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) has been responding to some of the most common claims that are gaining traction on social media. Let's take a look at one. Disinformation: The provision of pencils at polling places by the AEC is part of a plan by the AEC, or officers of the AEC, to change the referendum result by rubbing out votes. This is the response from the AEC to that claim: The AEC provides pencils as they do not smudge when a ballot paper is folded, they can be stored and re-used from one event to the next, they don't run dry in tropical locations and they are cheaper than other implements. Voters are permitted to bring their own pen to mark the ballot paper with if they wish. Pencil marks are not erased. Polling officials are never alone with ballot papers - there are layers of supervision in place during the count and scrutineers are able to be present during counting. Suggestions of a conspiracy to overturn a referendum result by erasing ballot papers simply does not account for the transparency or scale of the process, let alone the history of high integrity Australian electoral events.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: AEC debunks claim pencils are provided at the polls so votes can be 'rubbed out'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: William McDonnell has been appointed as chief financial officer of Insurance Australia Group (IAG), subject to regulatory approval. The insurance giant let the Australian Securities Exchange know about the appointment in the last 15 minutes. Mr McDonnell will be relocating to Sydney from London to take up the role. He's joining IAG from the global governance body, the Integrity Council for the Voluntary Carbon Market, where he spent two years as chief operating officer. He built that organisation from its foundation, leading it to be recognised as the world's standard-setter for carbon credits, and he oversaw the recent release of the Core Carbon Principles ad rulebook. Mr McDonnell also spent 15 years at the general insurer Royal & Sun Alliance Insurance Group, where for the last seven years he was group chief risk officer.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Here's the report from Reuters on what happened in US markets overnight: US stocks ended higher and the Nasdaq gained more than 1% on Wednesday, a day after a sell-off, as the latest economic data showed US private payrolls increased less than expected in September. Consumer discretionary rose 2%, leading S & P 500 sectors higher, as US Treasury yields eased off 16-year highs. The ADP National Employment Report was cheered by investors worried about rising interest rates and the likelihood that the Federal Reserve may need to keep rates higher for longer. "On a technical basis, we're probably a little bit oversold," said Oliver Pursche, senior vice president and advisor for Wealthspire Advisors in Westport, Connecticut. Recent weakness had brought the S & P 500 near its 200-day moving average, currently at around 4,203. "This September we saw a shift in both strategist and investor belief," he said. "It seems like it finally sunk in that interest rates are going to remain higher for longer, and that the idea that the Fed is going to cut rates any time soon is fictional." The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 127.17 points, or 0.39%, to 33,129.55, the S & P 500 gained 34.3 points, or 0.81%, at 4,263.75 and the Nasdaq Composite added 176.54 points, or 1.35%, at 13,236.01. Several mega-cap shares including Amazon.com were higher on the day.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Rally on Wall Street
